<exercise checkit-seed="0042" checkit-slug="M1" checkit-title="Multiplying matrices">
  <statement>
    <p>Of the following three matrices, only two may be multiplied.
      <md><mrow>A= \left[\begin{array}{ccc}
1 &amp; 0 &amp; -3 \\
-1 &amp; 1 &amp; 1 \\
1 &amp; 1 &amp; -4 \\
1 &amp; -3 &amp; 1
\end{array}\right]  &amp; &amp; B= \left[\begin{array}{ccc}
-5 &amp; 2 &amp; 6 \\
-3 &amp; 1 &amp; 3
\end{array}\right]  &amp; &amp; C= \left[\begin{array}{cccc}
1 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 &amp; -2 \\
-3 &amp; 1 &amp; -6 &amp; 5
\end{array}\right] </mrow></md>
      Explain which two can be multiplied and why. Then show how to find their product.</p>
  </statement>
  <answer>
    <me>CA= \left[\begin{array}{ccc}
0 &amp; 7 &amp; -9 \\
-5 &amp; -20 &amp; 39
\end{array}\right] </me>
  </answer>
</exercise>

